Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Jamie L. Pichla

records.addlTxt: 1:00 PM Defendant Jamie L. Pichla appeared by video.  Attorney Nicholas Grant Smith in court for Jamie L. Pichla.  Attorney Kristi S. Tlusty in court for State of Wisconsin. Victim notification has been complied. Attorney Tlusty recites the Deferred Entry of Judgment Agreement for the record. Attorney Smith informed the court that DE is waiving the preliminary hearing.  Court found waiver given freely and voluntarily.  Information filed with the court.  Court binds DE over for trial. DE waived any further reading of the information. DE enters a plea of no contest. Plea colloquy. Plea freely, voluntarily and intelligently; factual basis exists for the plea.  Court makes a finding of guilt. Statement made by Attorney Tlusty. Attorney Smith states that the first payment due November 1, 2022. Court accepts the Deferred Entry of Judgment Agreement and will hold the case open for 2 years with standard conditions. Court orders Defendant to pay restitution in the amount of $6,380 plus the restitution surcharge of $638. Defendant is to make payments in the amount of $292.42 each month starting November 1, 2022. Court also orders defendant to write an apology letter to G.J due within 30 days of sentencing and to be preapproved by the Victim Witness Coordinator.-JN
